Now if you have [Jackson][5] on your classpath (and have an [`&lt;mvc:annotation-driven&gt;`][6] setup), Spring would convert the incoming JSON to a UserStats object from the post body (because you added the `@RequestBody` annotation) and it would serialize the returned object to JSON (because you added the `@ResponseBody` annotation). So the Browser / Client would see this JSON result:

    { &quot;description&quot; : &quot;Elmer Fudd hates wacky wabbits&quot; }

